Robert\'92s violent fixation on Plaintiff came to a head when he learned that the soccer team they had played on together was going to play in the regional championship match. 
\i Id.
\i0  at 13. In his last session with Defendant before the match, Robert said Plaintiff \'93won\'92t play tomorrow,\'94 and that he \'93[c]an\'92t play if he can\'92t walk.\'94 
\i Id.
\i0  After issuing those threats, Robert \'93stormed out\'94 of his session with Defendant. 
\i Id.
\i0  Despite the specificity of the threats Robert made, Defendant did not believe that he would act on them because of: 1) the difficulty he would have in getting to Plaintiff; 2) the progress she believed they were making in therapy; and 3) her judgment that he would not have told her about his plans if he intended to act on them. 
\i Id. 
